T1  - The 2020 election campaign was over quickly
AN  - 2688125237
AB  - In one of the earliest social scientific studies of voting behavior, Paul Lazarsfeld (1944) observed that the 1940 presidential election campaign was over for most people before it even started. Drawn from a study of voters over the course of the campaign in Erie County, Ohio, Lazarsfeld and his colleagues observed that voting decisions were largely based on social position, as indicated by religious affiliation, economic status, and place of residence (urban or rural) (1944, 318-319). Since membership in these social groupings rarely changed, and never very quickly, the statics of a political campaign were far more impressive than the dynamics. This analysis suggested that political allegiances are deeply habituated, if not permanent, and that only a few voters make up their mind during the course of the campaign. In the 1940 election, for instance, 80 percent of votes were decided by the time of the nominating conventions (Lazarsfeld, 1944, 327). In short, campaigns matter, but their impact is typically small. The editor of Public Opinion Quarterly wrote, in a brief lead-in to Lazarsfeld's paper, that these findings would be disconcerting to politicians raising and spending money as if every vote hung in the balance. Lazarsfeld concluded with a technologically dated but perfectly apt metaphor: "The campaign is like the chemical bath which develops a photograph. The chemical influence is necessary to bring out the picture, but only the picture pre-structured on the plate can come out" (Lazarsfeld, 1944, 330).
